      "role": "user",
      "content": "hey i'm working on my dissertation and i keep hitting a wall with my p-values. if i get a p-value of 0.06, why is it technically \"not significant\" even if the effect size looks pretty big? it feels like the math is ignoring the trend.",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "A p-value of 0.06 is considered \"not statistically significant\" because it is greater than the conventional alpha level of 0.05. This means there is a 6% chance of observing your results, even if there were truly no effect in the population. While the effect size might be large, the p-value tells you the probability of seeing that effect by random chance alone, which is the hurdle you need to clear. Think of it as the difference between a strong signal and a noisy one.",
      "source": "target",
