    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "i get the \"statistical power\" part, but it still feels weirdly frustrating. like, when i look at the scatter plots, the data is clearly moving in one direction, but the math just says \"no.\" it's like there's this invisible force or some kind of chaotic interference making the results look messy. how do statisticians actually account for that kind of unpredictable noise that doesn't seem to follow a normal distribution?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "When the noise isn't behaving like a neat, predictable distribution, statisticians often turn to non-parametric tests that don't assume normality. These methods, like the Mann-Whitney U test, analyze the ranks of your data rather than the raw values themselves, making them robust to outliers and skewed distributions. Furthermore, you can investigate heterogeneity or outliers within your data to see if a specific subgroup or data point is driving the variability. Sometimes, the \"chaotic interference\" is actually a systematic issue with measurement or study design that needs addressing.",
      "source": "target",
